===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ar}} {{term|مسلم|مُسْلِمٌ|one who submits|tr=múslimun|sc=Arab}}, the [[w:Arabic grammar#Participle|participle]]<ref>also known as an "infinitive", compare Burns & Ralph, ''World Civilizations'', 5th ed., p. 371</ref> of {{term|أسلم|أسْلَمَ|he submitted|tr=ʼáslama|sc=Arab}}, [[Appendix:Arabic verb forms#Form IV|verb form IV]] from the [[triliteral]] root ''[[w:S-L-M|S-L-M]]'' "to be whole, intact". The related term {{term|إسلام|إسْلامٌ|sc=Arab|tr=’islāmun}} means literally "submission". In a religious sense, ''[[w:Islam|al-Islām]]'' translates to "faith, piety", and ''Muslim'' to "one who has (religious) faith or piety".

